# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clinical-decision-support
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A **clinical decision support system** (**CDSS**) is a form of health information technology that provides clinicians, staff, patients, or other individuals with knowledge and person-specific information to enhance decision-making in clinical workflows.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] CDSS tools include alerts and reminders, clinical guidelines, condition-specific order sets, patient data summaries, diagnostic support, and context-aware reference information.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] They often leverage artificial intelligence to analyze clinical data and help improve care quality and safety.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] CDSSs constitute a major topic in artificial intelligence in medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A clinical decision support system is an active knowledge system that uses variables of patient data to produce advice regarding health care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This implies that a CDSS is simply a decision support system focused on using knowledge management.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The main purpose of modern CDSS is to assist clinicians at the point of care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This means that clinicians interact with a CDSS to help to analyze and reach a diagnosis based on patient data for different diseases.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] In the early days, CDSSs were conceived to make decisions for the clinician in a literal manner.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The clinician would input the information and wait for the CDSS to output the "right" choice, and the clinician would simply act on that output.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] However, the modern methodology of using CDSSs to assist means that the clinician interacts with the CDSS, utilizing both their knowledge and the CDSS's, better to analyse the patient's data than either a human or a CDSS could do on their own.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Typically, a CDSS makes suggestions for the clinician to review, and the clinician is expected to pick out useful information from the presented results and discount erroneous CDSS suggestions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] An example of how a clinician might use a clinical decision support system is a diagnosis decision support system (DDSS).
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] DDSS requests some of the patient's data and, in response, proposes a set of possible diagnoses.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The physician then takes the output of the DDSS and determines which diagnoses are likely and which are not, and, if necessary, orders further tests to narrow down the diagnosis.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Another example of a CDSS would be a case-based reasoning (CBR) system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A CBR system might use previous case data to help determine the appropriate amount of beams and the optimal beam angles for use in radiotherapy for brain cancer patients; medical physicists and oncologists would then review the recommended treatment plan to determine its viability.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Another important classification of a CDSS is based on the timing of its use.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Physicians use these systems at the point of care to help them as they are dealing with a patient, with the timing of use being either pre-diagnosis, during diagnosis, or post-diagnosis.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Pre-diagnosis CDSS systems help the physician prepare the diagnoses.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] CDSSs help review and filter the physician's preliminary diagnostic choices to improve outcomes.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Post-diagnosis CDSS systems are used to mine data to derive connections between patients and their past medical history and clinical research to predict future events.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Early speculation that AI-based decision support would replace clinicians in common tasks has largely given way to a consensus around assistive models, in which AI augments rather than supplants clinical judgment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Contemporary deep learning-based systems, unlike earlier rule-based tools, can be trained directly on clinical data without manual rule authoring and integrated into electronic health record workflows at the point of care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Another approach, used by the National Health Service in England, is to use a CDSS to triage medical conditions out of hours by suggesting a suitable next step to the patient (e.g. call an ambulance, or see a general practitioner on the next working day).
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Most CDSSs consist of three parts: the knowledge base, an inference engine, and a mechanism to communicate.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The knowledge base contains the rules and associations of compiled data which most often take the form of IF-THEN rules.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] If this was a system for determining drug interactions, then a rule might be that IF drug X is taken AND drug Y is taken THEN alert the user.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Using another interface, an advanced user could edit the knowledge base to keep it up to date with new drugs.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The inference engine combines the rules from the knowledge base with the patient's data.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The communication mechanism allows the system to show the results to the user as well as have input into the system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] An expression language such as GELLO or CQL (Clinical Quality Language) is needed for expressing knowledge artefacts in a computable manner.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] For example: if a patient has diabetes mellitus, and if the last haemoglobin A1c test result was less than 7%, recommend re-testing if it has been over six months, but if the last test result was greater than or equal to 7%, then recommend re-testing if it has been over three months.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The current focus of the HL7 CDS WG is to build on the Clinical Quality Language (CQL).
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) has announced that it plans to use CQL for the specification of Electronic Clinical Quality Measures (eCQMs).
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] CDSSs which do not use a knowledge base use a form of artificial intelligence called machine learning, which allow computers to learn from past experiences and/or find patterns in clinical data.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This eliminates the need for writing rules and expert input.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] However, since systems based on machine learning cannot *explain* the reasons for their conclusions, most clinicians do not use them directly for diagnoses, reliability and accountability reasons.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Nevertheless, they can be useful as post-diagnostic systems, for suggesting patterns for clinicians to look into in more depth.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] As of 2012, three types of non-knowledge-based systems are support-vector machines, artificial neural networks and genetic algorithms.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Genetic algorithms are based on simplified evolutionary processes using directed selection to achieve optimal CDSS results.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The selection algorithms evaluate components of random sets of solutions to a problem.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The solutions that come out on top are then recombined and mutated and run through the process again.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This happens over and over until the proper solution is discovered.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] They are functionally similar to neural networks in that they are also "black boxes" that attempt to derive knowledge from patient data.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Non-knowledge-based networks often focus on a narrow list of symptoms, such as symptoms for a single disease, as opposed to the knowledge-based approach, which covers the diagnosis of many diseases.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] An example of a non-knowledge-based CDSS is a web server developed using a support vector machine for the prediction of gestational diabetes in Ireland.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The IOM had published a report in 1999, *To Err is Human*, which focused on the patient safety crisis in the United States, pointing to the incredibly high number of deaths.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This statistic attracted great attention to the quality of patient care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The Institute of Medicine (IOM) promoted the usage of health information technology, including clinical decision support systems, to advance the quality of patient care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] With the enactment of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 (ARRA), there was a push for widespread adoption of health information technology through the Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act (HITECH).
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Through these initiatives, more hospitals and clinics were integrating electronic medical records (EMRs) and computerized physician order entry (CPOE) within their health information processing and storage.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Despite the absence of laws, the CDSS vendors would almost certainly be viewed as having a legal duty of care to both the patients who may adversely be affected due to CDSS usage and the clinicians who may use the technology for patient care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] However, duties of care legal regulations are not explicitly defined yet.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A definition of "Meaningful use" has yet to be published.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The evidence of the effectiveness of CDSS is mixed.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] There are certain diseases which benefit more from CDSS than other disease entities.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A 2014 systematic review did not find a benefit in terms of risk of death when the CDSS was combined with the electronic health record.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] There may be some benefits, however, in terms of other outcomes.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A 2005 systematic review had concluded that CDSSs improved practitioner performance in 64% of the studies and patient outcomes in 13% of the studies.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] CDSSs features associated with improved practitioner performance included automatic electronic prompts rather than requiring user activation of the system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] However, later systematic reviews were less optimistic about the effects of CDS, with one from 2011 stating "There is a large gap between the postulated and empirically demonstrated benefits of [CDSS and other] eHealth technologies ... their cost-effectiveness has yet to be demonstrated".
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A five-year evaluation of the effectiveness of a CDSS in implementing rational treatment of bacterial infections for antimicrobial stewardship was published in 2014; according to the authors, it was the first long-term study of a CDSS.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Much effort has been put forth by many medical institutions and software companies to produce viable CDSSs to support all aspects of clinical tasks.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] However, with the complexity of clinical workflows and the demands on staff time high, care must be taken by the institution deploying the support system to ensure that the system becomes an integral part of the clinical workflow.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Some CDSSs have met with varying amounts of success, while others have suffered from common problems preventing or reducing successful adoption and acceptance.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Two sectors of the healthcare domain in which CDSSs have had a large impact are the pharmacy and billing sectors.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Commonly used pharmacy and prescription-ordering systems now perform batch-based checking orders for negative drug interactions and report warnings to the ordering professional.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Another sector of success for CDSS is in billing and claims filing.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Since many hospitals rely on Medicare reimbursements to stay in operation, systems have been created to help examine both a proposed treatment plan and the current rules of Medicare to suggest a plan that attempts to address both the care of the patient and the financial needs of the institution.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Other CDSSs that are aimed at diagnostic tasks have found success but are often very limited in deployment and scope.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The Leeds Abdominal Pain System went operational in 1971 for the University of Leeds hospital.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] It was reported to have produced a correct diagnosis in 91.8% of cases, compared to the clinicians' success rate of 79.6%.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Despite the wide range of efforts by institutions to produce and use these systems, widespread adoption and acceptance have still not yet been achieved for most offerings.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] One large roadblock to acceptance has historically been workflow integration.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A tendency to focus only on the functional decision-making core of the CDSS existed, causing a deficiency in planning how the clinician will use the product in situ.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] CDSSs were stand-alone applications, requiring the clinician to cease working on their current system, switch to the CDSS, input the necessary data (even if it had already been inputted into another system), and examine the results produced.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The additional steps break the flow from the clinician's perspective and cost precious time.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Clinical decision support systems face steep technical challenges in several areas.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Biological systems are profoundly complicated, and a clinical decision may utilise an enormous range of potentially relevant data.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Clinically, a large deterrent to CDSS acceptance is workflow integration.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Another source of contention with many medical support systems is that they produce a massive number of alerts.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] When systems produce a high volume of warnings (especially those that do not require escalation), besides the annoyance, clinicians may pay less attention to warnings, causing potentially critical alerts to be missed.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This phenomenon is called alert fatigue.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] One of the core challenges facing CDSS is difficulty in incorporating the extensive quantity of clinical research being published on an ongoing basis.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] In a given year, tens of thousands of clinical trials are published.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Currently, each one of these studies must be manually read, evaluated for scientific legitimacy, and incorporated into the CDSS in an accurate way.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] In 2004, it was stated that the process of gathering clinical data and medical knowledge and putting them into a form that computers can manipulate to assist in clinical decision-support is "still in its infancy".
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Nevertheless, it is more feasible for a business to do this centrally, even if incompletely, than for each doctor to try to keep up with all the research being published.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] In addition to being laborious, integration of new data can sometimes be difficult to quantify or incorporate into the existing decision support schema, particularly in instances where different clinical papers may appear conflicting.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Properly resolving these sorts of discrepancies is often the subject of clinical papers itself (see meta-analysis), which often take months to complete.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] In order for a CDSS to offer value, it must demonstrably improve clinical workflow or outcome.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Evaluation of CDSS quantifies its value to improve a system's quality and measure its effectiveness.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Because different CDSSs serve different purposes, no generic metric applies to all such systems; however, attributes such as consistency (with and with experts) often apply across a wide spectrum of systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The evaluation benchmark for a CDSS depends on the system's goal: for example, a diagnostic decision support system may be rated based upon the consistency and accuracy of its classification of disease (as compared to physicians or other decision support systems).
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] An evidence-based medicine system might be rated based upon a high incidence of patient improvement or higher financial reimbursement for care providers.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Implementing EHRs was an inevitable challenge.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This challenge is because it is a relatively uncharted area, and there are many issues and complications during the implementation phase of an EHR.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This can be seen in the numerous studies that have been undertaken.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] However, challenges in implementing electronic health records (EHRs) have received some attention.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Still, less is known about transitioning from legacy EHRs to newer systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] EHRs are a way to capture and utilise real-time data to provide high-quality patient care, ensuring efficiency and effective use of time and resources.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Incorporating EHR and CDSS together into the process of medicine has the potential to change the way medicine has been taught and practiced.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] It has been said that "the highest level of EHR is a CDSS".
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Since "clinical decision support systems (CDSS) are computer systems designed to impact clinician decision making about individual patients at the point in time that these decisions are made", it is clear that it would be beneficial to have a fully integrated CDSS and EHR.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Even though the benefits can be seen, fully implementing a CDSS integrated with an EHR has historically required significant planning by the healthcare facility/organisation for the CDSS to be successful and effective.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The success and effectiveness can be measured by the increased patient care being delivered and reduced adverse events occurring.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] In addition, there would be a saving of time and resources and benefits in terms of autonomy and financial benefits to the healthcare facility/organisation.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] As of July 2015, the planned transition to EHRs in Australia is facing difficulties.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Most healthcare facilities are still running completely paper-based systems; some are in a transition phase of scanned EHRs or moving towards such a transition phase.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] Victoria has attempted to implement EHR across the state with its HealthSMART program, but it has cancelled the project due to unexpectedly high costs.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] South Australia (SA) however is slightly more successful than Victoria in the implementation of an EHR.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This may be because all public healthcare organisations in SA are centrally run.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] SA is in the process of implementing "Enterprise patient administration system (EPAS)".
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This system is the foundation for all public hospitals and health care sites for an EHR within SA, and it was expected that by the end of 2014, all facilities in SA will be connected to it.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] This would allow for successful integration of CDSS into SA and increase the benefits of the EHR.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] By July 2015 it was reported that only 3 out of 75 health care facilities implemented EPAS.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] With the largest health system in the country and a federated rather than a centrally administered model, New South Wales is making consistent progress towards statewide implementation of EHRs.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The current iteration of the state's technology, eMR2, includes CDSS features such as a sepsis pathway for identifying at-risk patients based upon data input to the electronic record.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] As of June 2016, 93 of 194 sites in-scope for the initial roll-out had implemented eMR2.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The EBMEDS Clinical Decision Support service provided by Duodecim Medical Publications Ltd is used by more than 60% of Finnish public health care doctors.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] A study in the UK tested the Salford Medication Safety Dashboard (SMASH), a web-based CDSS application to help GPs and pharmacists find people in their electronic health records who might face safety hazards due to prescription errors.
[src:clinical-decision-support/clinical-decision-support-system] The dashboard was successfully used in identifying and helping patients with already registered unsafe prescriptions and later it helped monitoring new cases as they appeared.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The entered orders are communicated over a computer network to the medical staff or to the departments (pharmacy, laboratory, or radiology) responsible for fulfilling the order.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE reduces the time it takes to distribute and complete orders, while increasing efficiency by reducing transcription errors including preventing duplicate order entry, while simplifying inventory management and billing.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE is a form of patient management software.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Some textual data can be reduced to simple graphics.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE systems use terminology familiar to medical and nursing staff, but there are different terms used to classify and concatenate orders.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The application responding to, *i.e.*, performing, a request for services (orders) or producing an observation.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The filler can also originate requests for services (new orders), add additional services to existing orders, replace existing orders, put an order on hold, discontinue an order, release a held order, or cancel existing orders.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A request for a service from one application to a second application.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] In some cases an application is allowed to place orders with itself.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] One of several segments that can carry order information.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Future ancillary specific segments may be defined in subsequent releases of the Standard if they become necessary.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The application or individual originating a request for services (order).
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A list of associated orders coming from a single location regarding a single patient.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A grouping of orders used to standardize and expedite the ordering process for a common clinical scenario.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A grouping of orders used to standardize and automate a clinical process on behalf of a physician.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Physician orders can be standardized across the organization, and may be individualized for each prescriber or specialty through the use of order sets for common clinical scenarios.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Orders are communicated electronically to all departments and caregivers involved in carrying them out, which can improve response time and reduce conflicts with existing orders.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] to integrate decision logic with the order-entry interface.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE systems can provide allergy alerts, drug–drug, drug–food and drug–disease interaction checks, safe-dose-range checking, and review of orders for conflicts with other tests or treatments.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The order-entry workflow is generally designed to resemble familiar paper-based ordering forms, with the aim of making the system usable by new or infrequent users.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] ) at the time of entry to support charge capture.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Physicians have traditionally hand-written or verbally communicated orders for patient care, which are then transcribed by various individuals (such as unit clerks, nurses, and ancillary staff) before being carried out.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Handwritten reports or notes, manual order entry, non-standard abbreviations and poor legibility can lead to errors and injuries to patients.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A follow-up report from the Institute of Medicine (IOM) in 2001 advised use of electronic medication ordering, with computer- and internet-based information systems to support clinical decisions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Prescribing errors are the largest identified source of preventable hospital medical error, and a 2006 report by the IOM estimated that a hospitalized patient is exposed to a medication error each day of his or her stay.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Studies have estimated that CPOE implementation at all nonrural hospitals in the United States could prevent over 500,000 serious medication errors each year.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Other studies of CPOE have yielded evidence suggesting that the medication error rate can be reduced by approximately 80%, and that errors with potential for serious harm or death can be reduced by 55%.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Subsequent research has also reported mortality benefits.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A 2005 report from the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found that only 41 percent of prophylactic antibacterials were correctly stopped within 24 hours of completed surgery.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] In a subsequent eight-month evaluation, an intervention hospital that implemented a CPOE workflow designed to discontinue prophylactic antibacterials saw timely discontinuation rise from 38.8 percent of surgeries to 55.7 percent.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE and e-prescribing systems can also provide automatic dose-range alerts and drug-interaction checking.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Specialists in pharmacy informatics work with medical and nursing staff to apply these capabilities to medication use within the hospital.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Compared with paper-based ordering, CPOE produces legible, complete and standardized orders, eliminates several manual transcription steps, and routes orders electronically to the pharmacy, laboratory, radiology, and other ancillary departments responsible for carrying them out.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Because each order is captured in structured electronic form, the same data can simultaneously support clinical documentation, inventory tracking and billing without separate manual re-entry.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Realizing these advantages depends on adequate training, on careful design of the order-entry workflow, and on sustained organizational commitment to maintaining order sets and decision-support content after the initial deployment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE can introduce new types of errors not present in paper-based ordering.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Automation can also create a false sense of security, in which clinicians assume that orders accepted by the system have been verified for clinical appropriateness.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] In other settings, shortcut or default selections in the order interface can override non-standard medication regimens — for example for elderly or underweight patients — resulting in toxic doses.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Frequent alerts and warnings during order entry can interrupt workflow, leading to messages being ignored or overridden through alert fatigue.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE and automated drug dispensing were identified as a cause of error by 84% of over 500 health care facilities participating in a surveillance system operated by the United States Pharmacopoeia.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Introducing CPOE into a complex medical environment requires ongoing design changes to accommodate unique patients and care settings, close monitoring of automatic overrides, and continuing training of all users.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPOE systems can take years to install and configure.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] According to a study by RAND Health, the US healthcare system could save more than 81 billion dollars annually, reduce adverse medical events and improve the quality of care if it were to widely adopt CPOE and other health information technology.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] As more hospitals become aware of the financial benefits of CPOE, and more physicians with a familiarity with computers enter practice, increased use of CPOE is predicted.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Several high-profile failures of CPOE implementation have occurred, so a major effort must be focused on change management, including restructuring workflows, dealing with physicians' resistance to change, and creating a collaborative environment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] An early success with CPOE by the United States Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) is the Veterans Health Information Systems and Technology Architecture or VistA.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] A graphical user interface known as the Computerized Patient Record System (CPRS) allows health care providers to review and update a patient's record at any computer in the VA's over 1,000 healthcare facilities.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] CPRS includes the ability to place orders by CPOE, including medications, special procedures, x-rays, patient care nursing orders, diets and laboratory tests.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The world's first successful implementation of a CPOE system was at El Camino Hospital in Mountain View, California in the early 1970s.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The Medical Information System (MIS) was originally developed by a software and hardware team at Lockheed in Sunnyvale, California, which became the TMIS group at Technicon Instruments Corporation.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The MIS system used a light pen to allow physicians and nurses to quickly point and click items to be ordered.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] As of 2005, one of the largest projects for a national EHR is by the National Health Service (NHS) in the United Kingdom.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The goal of the NHS is to have 60,000,000 patients with a centralized electronic health record by 2010.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The plan involves a gradual roll-out commencing May 2006, providing general practices in England access to the National Programme for IT (NPfIT).
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The NHS component, known as the "Connecting for Health Programme", includes office-based CPOE for medication prescribing and test ordering and retrieval, although some concerns have been raised about patient safety features.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] In 2008, the Massachusetts Technology Collaborative and the New England Healthcare Institute (NEHI) published research showing that 1 in 10 patients admitted to a Massachusetts community hospital suffered a preventable medication error.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The study argued that Massachusetts hospitals could prevent 55,000 adverse drug events per year and save $170 million annually if they fully implemented CPOE.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The findings prompted the Commonwealth of Massachusetts to enact legislation requiring all hospitals to implement CPOE by 2012 as a condition of licensure.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] In addition, the study also concludes that it would cost approximately $2.1 million to implement a CPOE system, and a cost of $435,000 to maintain it in the state of Massachusetts while it saves annually about $2.7 million per hospital.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The hospitals will still see payback within 26 months through reducing hospitalizations generated by error.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Despite the advantages and cost savings, the CPOE is still not well adapted by many hospitals in the US.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The Leapfrog's 2008 survey showed that most hospitals are still not complying with having a fully implemented, effective CPOE system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] The CPOE requirement became more challenging to meet in 2008 because the Leapfrog introduced a new requirement: Hospitals must test their CPOE systems with Leapfrog's CPOE Evaluation Tool.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] So the number of hospitals in the survey considered to be fully meeting the standard dropped to 7% in 2008 from 11% the previous year.
[src:clinical-decision-support/computerized-physician-order-entry] Though the adoption rate seems very low in 2008, it is still an improvement from 2002 when only 2% of hospitals met this Leapfrog standard.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The EBM Pyramid is a tool that helps in visualizing the hierarchy of evidence in medicine, from least authoritative, like expert opinions, to most authoritative, like systematic reviews.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Adoption of evidence-based medicine is necessary in a human rights-based approach to public health and a precondition for accessing the right to health.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Medicine has a long history of scientific inquiry into the prevention, diagnosis, and treatment of human disease.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the 11th century AD, Avicenna, a Persian physician and philosopher, developed an approach to EBM that was mostly similar to current ideas and practises.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The concept of a controlled clinical trial was first described in 1662 by Jan Baptist van Helmont in reference to the practice of bloodletting.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The first published report describing the conduct and results of a controlled clinical trial was by James Lind, a Scottish naval surgeon who conducted research on scurvy during his time aboard HMS *Salisbury* in the Channel Fleet, while patrolling the Bay of Biscay.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Lind divided the sailors participating in his experiment into six groups, so that the effects of various treatments could be fairly compared.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Lind found improvement in symptoms and signs of scurvy among the group of men treated with lemons or oranges.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] He published a treatise describing the results of this experiment in 1753.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] An early critique of statistical methods in medicine was published in 1835, in Comtes Rendus de l'Académie des Sciences, Paris, by a man referred to as "Mr Civiale".
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] However, the concept met resistance from colleagues, as it implied that existing clinical practices lacked scientific rigor, even though this was likely true.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] To address this, Guyatt rebranded the approach as "Evidence-Based Medicine", a term first formally introduced in a 1991 editorial in the ACP Journal Club.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Although the name was coined in 1991, it took several years after and a concerted efforts of many other teams to define the foundations of this method.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Although more popular in medicine, the concept of "evidence-based" is spreading to other disciplines, such as the humanities, and to languages other than English, albeit at a slower pace.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Alvan Feinstein's publication of *Clinical Judgment* in 1967 focused attention on the role of clinical reasoning and identified biases that can affect it.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1972, Archie Cochrane published *Effectiveness and Efficiency*, which described the lack of controlled trials supporting many practices that had previously been assumed to be effective.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1973, John Wennberg began to document wide variations in how physicians practiced.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Eddy described errors in clinical reasoning and gaps in evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the mid-1980s, Alvin Feinstein, David Sackett and others published textbooks on clinical epidemiology, which translated epidemiological methods to physician decision-making.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Toward the end of the 1980s, a group at RAND showed that large proportions of procedures performed by physicians were considered inappropriate even by the standards of their own experts.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Eddy first began to use the term 'evidence-based' in 1987 in workshops and a manual commissioned by the Council of Medical Specialty Societies to teach formal methods for designing clinical practice guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The manual was eventually published by the American College of Physicians.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The pertinent evidence must be identified, described, and analyzed.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The policymakers must determine whether the policy is justified by the evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] A rationale must be written." He discussed evidence-based policies in several other papers published in *JAMA* in the spring of 1990.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Those papers were part of a series of 28 published in *JAMA* between 1990 and 1997 on formal methods for designing population-level guidelines and policies.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The term 'evidence-based medicine' was introduced slightly later, in the context of medical education.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the autumn of 1990, Gordon Guyatt used it in an unpublished description of a program at McMaster University for prospective or new medical students.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Guyatt and others first published the term two years later (1992) to describe a new approach to teaching the practice of medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Between 1993 and 2000, the Evidence-Based Medicine Working Group at McMaster University published the methods to a broad physician audience in a series of 25 "Users' Guides to the Medical Literature" in *JAMA*.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The two original definitions highlight important differences in how evidence-based medicine is applied to populations versus individuals.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] When designing guidelines applied to large groups of people in settings with relatively little opportunity for modification by individual physicians, evidence-based policymaking emphasizes that good evidence should exist to document a test's or treatment's effectiveness.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the setting of individual decision-making, practitioners can be given greater latitude in how they interpret research and combine it with their clinical judgment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the area of evidence-based guidelines and policies, the explicit insistence on evidence of effectiveness was introduced by the American Cancer Society in 1980.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) began issuing guidelines for preventive interventions based on evidence-based principles in 1984.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1985, the Blue Cross Blue Shield Association applied strict evidence-based criteria for covering new technologies.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Beginning in 1987, specialty societies such as the American College of Physicians, and voluntary health organizations such as the American Heart Association, wrote many evidence-based guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1991, Kaiser Permanente, a managed care organization in the US, began an evidence-based guidelines program.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1991, Richard Smith wrote an editorial in the *British Medical Journal* and introduced the ideas of evidence-based policies in the UK.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1993, the Cochrane Collaboration created a network of 13 countries to produce systematic reviews and guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1997, the US Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ, then known as the Agency for Health Care Policy and Research, or AHCPR) established Evidence-based Practice Centers (EPCs) to produce evidence reports and technology assessments to support the development of guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the same year, a National Guideline Clearinghouse that followed the principles of evidence-based policies was created by AHRQ, the AMA, and the American Association of Health Plans (now America's Health Insurance Plans).
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1999, the National Institute for Clinical Excellence (NICE) was created in the UK to circulate evidence and guidance on treatments within the NHS.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the area of medical education, medical schools in Canada, the US, the UK, Australia, and other countries now offer programs that teach evidence-based medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] A 2009 study of UK programs found that more than half of UK medical schools offered some training in evidence-based medicine, although the methods and content varied considerably, and EBM teaching was restricted by lack of curriculum time, trained tutors and teaching materials.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Many programs have been developed to help individual physicians gain better access to evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] For example, UpToDate was created in the early 1990s.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The Cochrane Collaboration began publishing evidence reviews in 1993.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 1995, BMJ Publishing Group launched Clinical Evidence, a 6-monthly periodical that provided brief summaries of the current state of evidence about important clinical questions for clinicians.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] By 2000, use of the term *evidence-based* had extended to other levels of the health care system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] An example is evidence-based health services, which seek to increase the competence of health service decision makers and the practice of evidence-based medicine at the organizational or institutional level.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The multiple tributaries of evidence-based medicine share an emphasis on the importance of incorporating evidence from formal research in medical policies and decisions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Differences also exist regarding the extent to which it is feasible to incorporate individual-level information in decisions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Thus, evidence-based guidelines and policies may not readily "hybridise" with experience-based practices orientated towards ethical clinical judgement, and can lead to contradictions, contest, and unintended crises.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The most effective "knowledge leaders" (managers and clinical leaders) use a broad range of management knowledge in their decision making, rather than just formal evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Evidence-based guidelines may provide the basis for governmentality in health care, and consequently play a central role in the governance of contemporary health care systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] For the purposes of medical education and individual-level decision making, five steps of EBM in practice were described in 1992 and the experience of delegates attending the 2003 Conference of Evidence-Based Health Care Teachers and Developers was summarized into five steps and published in 2005.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Systematic reviews of published research studies are a major part of the evaluation of particular treatments.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The Cochrane Collaboration is one of the best-known organisations that conducts systematic reviews.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Like other producers of systematic reviews, it requires authors to provide a detailed study protocol as well as a reproducible plan of their literature search and evaluations of the evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] After the best evidence is assessed, treatment is categorized as (1) likely to be beneficial, (2) likely to be harmful, or (3) without evidence to support either benefit or harm.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Evidence-based medicine categorizes different types of clinical evidence and rates or grades them according to the strength of their freedom from the various biases that beset medical research.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] For example, the strongest evidence for therapeutic interventions is provided by systematic review of randomized, well-blinded, placebo-controlled trials with allocation concealment and complete follow-up involving a homogeneous patient population and medical condition.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Several organizations have developed grading systems for assessing the quality of evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Another example are the Oxford CEBM Levels of Evidence published by the Centre for Evidence-Based Medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] First released in September 2000, the Levels of Evidence provide a way to rank evidence for claims about prognosis, diagnosis, treatment benefits, treatment harms, and screening, which most grading schemes do not address.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The original CEBM Levels were Evidence-Based On Call to make the process of finding evidence feasible and its results explicit.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 2011, an international team redesigned the Oxford CEBM Levels to make them more understandable and to take into account recent developments in evidence ranking schemes.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In 2000, a system was developed by the Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development and Evaluation (GRADE) working group.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The GRADE system takes into account more dimensions than just the quality of medical research.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] It requires users who are performing an assessment of the quality of evidence, usually as part of a systematic review, to consider the impact of different factors on their confidence in the results.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Authors of GRADE tables assign one of four levels to evaluate the quality of evidence, on the basis of their confidence that the observed effect (a numeric value) is close to the true effect.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The confidence value is based on judgments assigned in five different domains in a structured manner.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The GRADE working group defines 'quality of evidence' and 'strength of recommendations' based on the quality as two different concepts that are commonly confused with each other.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Systematic reviews may include randomized controlled trials that have low risk of bias, or observational studies that have high risk of bias.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the case of randomized controlled trials, the quality of evidence is high but can be downgraded in five different domains.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In the case of observational studies per GRADE, the quality of evidence starts off lower and may be upgraded in three domains in addition to being subject to downgrading.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In guidelines and other publications, recommendation for a clinical service is classified by the balance of risk versus benefit and the level of evidence on which this information is based.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] GRADE guideline panelists may make strong or weak recommendations on the basis of further criteria.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Some of the important criteria are the balance between desirable and undesirable effects (not considering cost), the quality of the evidence, values and preferences and costs (resource utilization).
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Despite the differences between systems, the purposes are the same: to guide users of clinical research information on which studies are likely to be most valid.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Evidence-based medicine attempts to express clinical benefits of tests and treatments using mathematical methods.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Evidence-based medicine attempts to objectively evaluate the quality of clinical research by critically assessing techniques reported by researchers in their publications.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] There are a number of limitations and criticisms of evidence-based medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Despite the emphasis on evidence-based medicine, unsafe or ineffective medical practices may occur.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Contributing factors include clinicians not keeping up with or acting on current evidence, the rapid pace of scientific change, financial incentives, and patient demand for tests or treatments.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Even when the evidence unequivocally shows that a treatment is either not safe or ineffective, it may take many years for other treatments to be adopted.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Several factors may contribute to lack of uptake or implementation of evidence-based recommendations.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] These include lack of awareness at the individual clinician or patient (micro) level, lack of institutional support at the organisation level (meso) level or higher at the policy (macro) level.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] In other cases, significant change can require a generation of physicians to be replaced by physicians who were trained with more recent evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Revision of clinical guidelines to include an implementation plan may facilitate uptake of new procedures, including analysis of the context, identifying barriers and facilitators, and designing strategies to address them.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Training in evidence based medicine is offered across the continuum of medical education.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Educational competencies have been created for the education of health care professionals.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] The Berlin questionnaire and the Fresno Test are validated instruments for assessing the effectiveness of education in evidence-based medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] These questionnaires have been used in diverse settings.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] A Campbell systematic review that included 24 trials examined the effectiveness of e-learning in improving evidence-based health care knowledge and practice.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] It was found that e-learning, compared to no learning, improves evidence-based health care knowledge and skills but not attitudes and behaviour.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] No difference in outcomes is present when comparing e-learning with face-to-face learning.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] Combining e-learning and face-to-face learning (blended learning) has a positive impact on evidence-based knowledge, skills, attitude and behavior.
[src:clinical-decision-support/evidence-based-medicine] As a form of e-learning, some medical school students engage in editing Wikipedia to increase their EBM skills, and some students construct EBM materials to develop their skills in communicating medical knowledge.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In artificial intelligence (AI), an **expert system** is a computer system emulating the decision-making ability of a human expert.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems are designed to solve complex problems by reasoning through bodies of knowledge, represented mainly as if–then rules rather than through conventional procedural programming code.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems were among the first truly successful forms of AI software.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] They were created in the 1970s and then proliferated in the 1980s, being then widely regarded as the future of AI — before the advent of successful artificial neural networks.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] An expert system is divided into two subsystems: 1) a *knowledge base*, which represents facts and rules; and 2) an *inference engine*, which applies the rules to the known facts to deduce new facts, and can include explaining and debugging abilities.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Soon after the dawn of modern computers in the late 1940s and early 1950s, researchers started realizing the immense potential these machines had for modern society.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] One of the first challenges was to make such machines able to “think” like humans – in particular, making these machines able to make important decisions the way humans do.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The medical–healthcare field presented the tantalizing challenge of enabling these machines to make medical diagnostic decisions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Thus, in the late 1950s, right after the information age had fully arrived, researchers started experimenting with the prospect of using computer technology to emulate human decision making.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] For example, biomedical researchers started creating computer-aided systems for diagnostic applications in medicine and biology.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These early diagnostic systems used patients’ symptoms and laboratory test results as inputs to generate a diagnostic outcome.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These systems were often described as the early forms of expert systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] However, researchers realized that there were significant limits when using traditional methods such as flow charts, statistical pattern matching, or probability theory.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This previous situation gradually led to the development of expert systems, which used knowledge-based approaches.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These expert systems in medicine were the MYCIN expert system, the Internist-I expert system and later, in the middle of the 1980s, the CADUCEUS.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems were formally introduced around 1965 by the Stanford Heuristic Programming Project led by Edward Feigenbaum, who is sometimes termed the "father of expert systems"; other key early contributors were Bruce Buchanan and Randall Davis.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The Stanford researchers tried to identify domains where expertise was highly valued and complex, such as diagnosing infectious diseases (Mycin) and identifying unknown organic molecules (Dendral).
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems became some of the first truly successful forms of artificial intelligence (AI) software.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Research on expert systems was also active in Europe.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In the US, the focus tended to be on the use of production rule systems, first on systems hard coded on top of Lisp programming environments and then on expert system shells developed by vendors such as Intellicorp.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In Europe, research focused more on systems and expert systems shells developed in Prolog.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The advantage of Prolog systems was that they employed a form of rule-based programming that was based on formal logic.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] One such early expert system shell based on Prolog was APES.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] One of the first use cases of Prolog and APES was in the legal area namely, the encoding of a large portion of the British Nationality Act.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In the 1980s, expert systems proliferated.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Universities offered expert system courses and two-thirds of the Fortune 500 companies applied the technology in daily business activities.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Interest was international with the Fifth Generation Computer Systems project in Japan and increased research funding in Europe.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In 1981, the first IBM PC, with the PC DOS operating system, was introduced.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The imbalance between the low cost of the relatively powerful chips in the PC, compared to the much more expensive cost of processing power in the mainframes that dominated the corporate IT world at the time, created a new type of architecture for corporate computing, termed the client–server model.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Calculations and reasoning could be performed at a fraction of the price of a mainframe using a PC.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This model also enabled business units to bypass corporate IT departments and directly build their own applications.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] As a result, client-server had a tremendous impact on the expert systems market.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems were already outliers in much of the business world, requiring new skills that many IT departments did not have and were not eager to develop.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] They were a natural fit for new PC-based shells that promised to put application development into the hands of end users and experts.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Until then, the main development environment for expert systems had been high end Lisp machines from Xerox, Symbolics, and Texas Instruments.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] With the rise of the PC and client-server computing, vendors such as Intellicorp and Inference Corporation shifted their priorities to developing PC-based tools.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Also, new vendors, often financed by venture capital started appearing regularly.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The first expert system to be used in a design capacity for a large-scale product was the Synthesis of Integral Design (SID) software program, developed in 1982.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Written in Lisp, SID generated 93% of the VAX 9000 CPU logic gates.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Input to the software was a set of rules created by several expert logic designers.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] SID expanded the rules and generated software logic synthesis routines many times the size of the rules themselves.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Surprisingly, the combination of these rules resulted in an overall design that exceeded the capabilities of the experts themselves, and in many cases out-performed the human counterparts.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] While some rules contradicted others, top-level control parameters for speed and area provided the tie-breaker.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The program was highly controversial but used nevertheless due to project budget constraints.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It was terminated by logic designers after the VAX 9000 project completion.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] During the years before the middle of the 1970s, the expectations of what expert systems can accomplish in many fields tended to be extremely optimistic.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] At the start of these early studies, researchers were hoping to develop entirely automatic (i.e., completely computerized) expert systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The expectations of people of what computers can do were frequently too idealistic.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This situation radically changed after Richard M.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Karp published his breakthrough paper: “Reducibility among Combinatorial Problems” in the early 1970s.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Thanks to Karp's work, together with other scholars, like Hubert L.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Dreyfus, it became clear that there are certain limits and possibilities when one designs computer algorithms.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] His findings describe what computers can do and what they cannot do.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Many of the computational problems related to this type of expert systems have certain pragmatic limits.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These findings laid down the groundwork that led to the next developments in the field.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In the 1990s and beyond, the term *expert system* and the idea of a standalone AI system mostly dropped from the IT lexicon.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] One is that "expert systems failed": the IT world moved on because expert systems did not deliver on their over hyped promise.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The other is the mirror opposite, that expert systems were simply victims of their success: as IT professionals grasped concepts such as rule engines, such tools migrated from being standalone tools for developing special purpose *expert* systems, to being one of many standard tools.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Other researchers suggest that Expert Systems caused inter-company power struggles when the IT organization lost its exclusivity in software modifications to users or Knowledge Engineers.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In the first decade of the 2000s, there was a "resurrection" for the technology, while using the term *rule-based systems*, with significant success stories and adoption.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Many of the leading major business application suite vendors (such as SAP, Siebel, and Oracle) integrated expert system abilities into their suite of products as a way to specify business logic.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Rule engines are no longer simply for defining the rules an expert would use but for any type of complex, volatile, and critical business logic; they often go hand in hand with business process automation and integration environments.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It can be argued that expert systems have moved into the area of business rules and business rules management systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] An expert system is an example of a knowledge-based system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems were the first commercial systems to use a knowledge-based architecture.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In general view, an expert system includes the following components: a knowledge base, an inference engine, an explanation facility, a knowledge acquisition facility, and a user interface.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The knowledge base represents facts about the world.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In early expert systems such as Mycin and Dendral, these facts were represented mainly as flat assertions about variables.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In later expert systems developed with commercial shells, the knowledge base took on more structure and used concepts from object-oriented programming.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The world was represented as classes, subclasses, and instances and assertions were replaced by values of object instances.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The rules worked by querying and asserting values of the objects.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The inference engine is an automated reasoning system that evaluates the current state of the knowledge-base, applies relevant rules, and then asserts new knowledge into the knowledge base.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The inference engine may also include abilities for explanation, so that it can explain to a user the chain of reasoning used to arrive at a particular conclusion by tracing back over the firing of rules that resulted in the assertion.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] There are mainly two modes for an inference engine: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The different approaches are dictated by whether the inference engine is being driven by the antecedent (left hand side) or the consequent (right hand side) of the rule.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In forward chaining an antecedent fires and asserts the consequent.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] A simple example of forward chaining would be to assert Man(Socrates) to the system and then trigger the inference engine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It would match R1 and assert Mortal(Socrates) into the knowledge base.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Backward chaining is a bit less straight forward.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In backward chaining the system looks at possible conclusions and works backward to see if they might be true.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] So if the system was trying to determine if Mortal(Socrates) is true it would find R1 and query the knowledge base to see if Man(Socrates) is true.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] One of the early innovations of expert systems shells was to integrate inference engines with a user interface.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This could be especially powerful with backward chaining.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] If the system needs to know a particular fact but does not, then it can simply generate an input screen and ask the user if the information is known.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] So in this example, it could use R1 to ask the user if Socrates was a Man and then use that new information accordingly.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The use of rules to explicitly represent knowledge also enabled explanation abilities.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In English, if the user asked "Why is Socrates Mortal?" the system would reply "Because all men are mortal and Socrates is a man".
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] A significant area for research was the generation of explanations from the knowledge base in natural English rather than simply by showing the more formal but less intuitive rules.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] As expert systems evolved, many new techniques were incorporated into various types of inference engines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The goal of knowledge-based systems is to make the critical information required for the system to work explicit rather than implicit.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In a traditional computer program, the logic is embedded in code that can typically only be reviewed by an IT specialist.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] With an expert system, the goal was to specify the rules in a format that was intuitive and easily understood, reviewed, and even edited by domain experts rather than IT experts.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The benefits of this explicit knowledge representation were rapid development and ease of maintenance.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Ease of maintenance is the most obvious benefit.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] First, by removing the need to write conventional code, many of the normal problems that can be caused by even small changes to a system could be avoided with expert systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Essentially, the logical flow of the program (at least at the highest level) was simply a given for the system, simply invoke the inference engine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This also was a reason for the second benefit: rapid prototyping.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] With an expert system shell it was possible to enter a few rules and have a prototype developed in days rather than the months or year typically associated with complex IT projects.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] A claim for expert system shells that was often made was that they removed the need for trained programmers and that experts could develop systems themselves.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In reality, this was seldom if ever true.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] While the rules for an expert system were more comprehensible than typical computer code, they still had a formal syntax where a misplaced comma or other character could cause havoc as with any other computer language.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Also, as expert systems moved from prototypes in the lab to deployment in the business world, issues of integration and maintenance became far more critical.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Inevitably demands to integrate with, and take advantage of, large legacy databases and systems arose.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] To accomplish this, integration required the same skills as any other type of system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Multiple expertise: Several expert systems can be run simultaneously to solve a problem. and gain a higher level of expertise than a human expert.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Explanation: Expert systems always describe of how the problem was solved.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Fast response: The expert systems are fast and able to solve a problem in real-time.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Reduced cost: The cost of expertise for each user is significantly reduced.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The most common disadvantage cited for expert systems in the academic literature is the knowledge acquisition problem.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Obtaining the time of domain experts for any software application is always difficult, but for expert systems it was especially difficult because the experts were by definition highly valued and in constant demand by the organization.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] As a result of this problem, a great deal of research in the later years of expert systems was focused on tools for knowledge acquisition, to help automate the process of designing, debugging, and maintaining rules defined by experts.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] However, when looking at the life-cycle of expert systems in actual use, other problems – essentially the same problems as those of any other large system – seem at least as critical as knowledge acquisition: integration, access to large databases, and performance.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Performance could be especially problematic because early expert systems were built using tools (such as earlier Lisp versions) that interpreted code expressions without first compiling them.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This provided a powerful development environment, but with the drawback that it was virtually impossible to match the efficiency of the fastest compiled languages (such as C).
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] As a result, much effort in the later stages of expert system tool development was focused on integrating with legacy environments such as COBOL and large database systems, and on porting to more standard platforms.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These issues were resolved mainly by the client–server paradigm shift, as PCs were gradually accepted in the IT environment as a legitimate platform for serious business system development and as affordable minicomputer servers provided the processing power needed for AI applications.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Another major challenge of expert systems emerges when the size of the knowledge base increases.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This causes the processing complexity to increase.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] For instance, when an expert system with 100 million rules was envisioned as the ultimate expert system, it became obvious that such system would be too complex and it would face too many computational problems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] An inference engine would have to be able to process huge numbers of rules to reach a decision.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] How to verify that decision rules are consistent with each other is also a challenge when there are too many rules.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Usually such problem leads to a satisfiability (SAT) formulation.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] This is a well-known NP-complete problem Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] If we assume only binary variables, say n of them, and then the corresponding search space is of size 2 $^{n}$ .
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Thus, the search space can grow exponentially.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] There are also questions on how to prioritize the use of the rules to operate more efficiently, or how to resolve ambiguities (for instance, if there are too many else-if sub-structures within one rule) and so on.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Other problems are related to the overfitting and overgeneralization effects when using known facts and trying to generalize to other cases not described explicitly in the knowledge base.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Such problems exist with methods that employ machine learning approaches too.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Another problem related to the knowledge base is how to make updates of its knowledge quickly and effectively.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Also how to add a new piece of knowledge (i.e., where to add it among many rules) is challenging.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Modern approaches that rely on machine learning methods are easier in this regard.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Because of the above challenges, it became clear that new approaches to AI were required instead of rule-based technologies.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These new approaches are based on the use of machine learning techniques, along with the use of feedback mechanisms.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Expert systems require knowledge engineers to input the data, data acquisition is very hard.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The expert system may choose the most inappropriate method for solving a particular problem.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Problems of ethics in the use of any form of AI are very relevant at present.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It is a closed world with specific knowledge, in which there is no deep perception of concepts and their interrelationships until an expert provides them.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Hayes-Roth divides expert systems applications into 10 categories illustrated in the following table.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The example applications were not in the original Hayes-Roth table, and some of them arose well afterward.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Any application that is not footnoted is described in the Hayes-Roth book.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Also, while these categories provide an intuitive framework to describe the space of expert systems applications, they are not rigid categories, and in some cases an application may show traits of more than one category.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Hearsay was an early attempt at solving voice recognition through an expert systems approach.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] For the most part this category of expert systems was not all that successful.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Hearsay and all interpretation systems are essentially pattern recognition systems—looking for patterns in noisy data.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] In the case of Hearsay recognizing phonemes in an audio stream.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Other early examples were analyzing sonar data to detect Russian submarines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] These kinds of systems proved much more amenable to a neural network AI solution than a rule-based approach.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] CADUCEUS and MYCIN were medical diagnosis systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The user describes their symptoms to the computer as they would to a doctor and the computer returns a medical diagnosis.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Dendral was a tool to study hypothesis formation in the identification of organic molecules.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The general problem it solved—designing a solution given a set of constraints—was one of the most successful areas for early expert systems applied to business domains such as salespeople configuring Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) VAX computers and mortgage loan application development.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] SMH.PAL is an expert system for the assessment of students with multiple disabilities.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] GARVAN-ES1 was a medical expert system, developed at the Garvan Institute of Medical Research, that provided automated clinical diagnostic comments on endocrine reports from a pathology laboratory.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It was one of the first medical expert systems to go into routine clinical use internationally and the first expert system to be used for diagnosis daily in Australia.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] The system was written in "C" and ran on a PDP-11 in 64K of memory.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It had 661 rules that were compiled; not interpreted.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Mistral is an expert system to monitor dam safety, developed in the 1990s by Ismes in Italy.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It gets data from an automatic monitoring system and performs a diagnosis of the state of the dam.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Its first copy was installed in 1992 on the Ridracoli Dam in Italy.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] It has been installed on several other dams in Italy and abroad (e.g., Itaipu Dam in Brazil), and on landslide sites under the name of Eydenet, and on monuments under the name of Kaleidos.
[src:clinical-decision-support/expert-system] Mistral is a registered trade mark of CESI.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] A **medical algorithm** is any computation, formula, statistical survey, nomogram, or look-up table, useful in healthcare.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Medical algorithms include decision tree approaches to healthcare treatment (e.g., if symptoms A, B, and C are evident, then use treatment X) and also less clear-cut tools aimed at reducing or defining uncertainty.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] A medical prescription is also a type of medical algorithm.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Medical algorithms are part of a broader field which is usually fit under the aims of medical informatics and medical decision-making.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Medical decisions occur in several areas of medical activity including medical test selection, diagnosis, therapy and prognosis, and automatic control of medical equipment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] In relation to logic-based and artificial neural network-based clinical decision support systems, which are also computer applications used in the medical decision-making field, algorithms are less complex in architecture, data structure and user interface.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Medical algorithms are not necessarily implemented using digital computers.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] In fact, many of them can be represented on paper, in the form of diagrams, nomographs, etc.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] A wealth of medical information exists in the form of published medical algorithms.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] These algorithms range from simple calculations to complex outcome predictions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Most clinicians use only a small subset routinely.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] A common class of algorithms are embedded in guidelines on the choice of treatments produced by many national, state, financial and local healthcare organisations and provided as knowledge resources for day to day use and for induction of new physicians.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] A field which has gained particular attention is the choice of medications for psychiatric conditions.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] In the United Kingdom, guidelines or algorithms for this have been produced by most of the circa 500 primary care trusts, substantially all of the circa 100 secondary care psychiatric units and many of the circa 10 000 general practices.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] In the US, there is a national (federal) initiative to provide them for all states, and by 2005 six states were adapting the approach of the Texas Medication Algorithm Project or otherwise working on their production.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] A grammar—the Arden syntax—exists for describing algorithms in terms of medical logic modules.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] An approach such as this should allow exchange of MLMs between doctors and establishments, and enrichment of the common stock of tools.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] The intended purpose of medical algorithms is to improve and standardize decisions made in the delivery of medical care.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Medical algorithms assist in standardizing selection and application of treatment regimens, with algorithm automation intended to reduce potential introduction of errors.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Some attempt to predict the outcome, for example critical care scoring systems.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Computerized health diagnostics algorithms can provide timely clinical decision support, improve adherence to evidence-based guidelines, and be a resource for education and research.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Medical algorithms based on best practice can assist everyone involved in delivery of standardized treatment via a wide range of clinical care providers.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Many are presented as protocols and it is a key task in training to ensure people step outside the protocol when necessary.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] In our present state of knowledge, generating hints and producing guidelines may be less satisfying to the authors, but more appropriate.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] In common with most science and medicine, algorithms whose contents are not wholly available for scrutiny and open to improvement should be regarded with suspicion.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-algorithm] Computations obtained from medical algorithms should be compared with, and tempered by, clinical knowledge and physician judgment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] A **medical guideline** (also called a **clinical guideline**, **standard treatment guideline**, or **clinical practice guideline**) is a document with the aim of guiding decisions and criteria regarding diagnosis, management, and treatment in specific areas of healthcare.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Such documents have been in use for thousands of years during the entire history of medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] However, in contrast to previous approaches, which were often based on tradition or authority, modern medical guidelines are based on an examination of current evidence within the paradigm of evidence-based medicine.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] They usually include summarized consensus statements on best practice in healthcare.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] A healthcare provider is obliged to know the medical guidelines of their profession, and has to decide whether to follow the recommendations of a guideline for an individual treatment.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Modern clinical guidelines identify, summarize and evaluate the highest quality evidence and most current data about prevention, diagnosis, prognosis, therapy including dosage of medications, risk/benefit and cost-effectiveness.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Then they define the most important questions related to clinical practice and identify all possible decision options and their outcomes.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Some guidelines contain decision or computation algorithms to be followed.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Thus, they integrate the identified decision points and respective courses of action with the clinical judgement and experience of practitioners.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Many guidelines place the treatment alternatives into classes to help providers in deciding which treatment to use.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] It has been demonstrated repeatedly that the use of guidelines by healthcare providers such as hospitals is an effective way of achieving the objectives listed above, although they are not the only ones.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Guidelines are usually produced at national or international levels by medical associations or governmental bodies, such as the United States Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Local healthcare providers may produce their own set of guidelines or adapt them from existing top-level guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Healthcare payers such as insurers practicing utilization management also publish guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Special computer software packages known as guideline execution engines have been developed to facilitate the use of medical guidelines in concert with an electronic medical record system.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] The Guideline Interchange Format (GLIF) is a computer representation format for clinical guidelines that can be used with such engines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] The US and other countries maintain medical guideline clearinghouses.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] In the US, the National Guideline Clearinghouse maintains a catalog of high-quality guidelines published by various health and medical associations.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] In the United Kingdom, clinical practice guidelines are published primarily by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE).
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] In The Netherlands, two bodies—the Institute for Healthcare Improvement (CBO) and College of General Practitioners (NHG)—have published specialist and primary care guidelines, respectively.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] In Germany, the German Agency for Quality in Medicine (ÄZQ) coordinates a national program for disease management guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] All these organisations are now members of the Guidelines International Network (G-I-N), an international network of organisations and individuals involved in clinical practice guidelines.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Checklists have been used in medical practice to attempt to ensure that clinical practice guidelines are followed.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] An example is the Surgical Safety Checklist developed for the World Health Organization by Atul Gawande.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] According to a meta-analysis after introduction of the checklist mortality dropped by 23% and all complications by 40%, but further high-quality studies are required to make the meta-analysis more robust.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Guidelines may have both methodological problems and conflict of interest.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] As such, the quality of guidelines may vary substantially, especially for guidelines that are published online and have not had to follow methodological reporting standards often required by reputable clearinghouses.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Guidelines may make recommendations that are stronger than the supporting evidence.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Patients and caregivers are frequently excluded from clinical guidelines development, in part because there is a lack of guidance for how to include them in the process.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Guidelines may lose their clinical relevance as they age and newer research emerges.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] Even 20% of strong recommendations, especially when based on opinion rather than trials, from practice guidelines may be retracted.
[src:clinical-decision-support/medical-guideline] In response to many of the problems with traditional guidelines, the BMJ created a new series of trustworthy guidelines focused on the most pressing medical issues called *BMJ* Rapid Recommendations.
